  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Calculating Points Before Job Search</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Many people accept job offers then discover they don't have 70 points. Calculate your score first using migration.gv.at. If borderline, prioritize getting German language certification (A2 = 10 points, B1 = 15 points) before applying.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing Document Apostille/Translation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">All foreign documents must be apostilled and translated by certified translators. This takes 2-4 weeks and many applications are delayed because documents weren't properly prepared. Start this process immediately after accepting a job offer.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming You Can Work While Application is Pending</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Unlike some countries, you cannot work in Austria while your Red-White-Red Card is being processed (unless you have another valid work authorization). Plan finances for the 8-12 week wait or apply from your home country.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting to Register Address (Meldezettel)</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register your address at the Magistrat/Gemeindeamt within 3 days of moving in. This is required to collect your Red-White-Red Card and for everything administrative. Without Meldezettel, you can't open bank accounts or complete the card process.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Understanding the Two-Year Transition</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The initial Red-White-Red Card is tied to your employer for 2 years. After that, you get the "Plus" version with any-employer work rights. If you want to change jobs in the first 2 years, you need a new card application. Plan accordingly.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Austria -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Austria</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria has excellent healthcare with universal coverage through ÖGK. Quality is high, wait times reasonable, and costs are covered through social insurance. Most expats find the system works well once they understand how to navigate it.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Austrian Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">E-Card System</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You'll receive an e-card (electronic health card) after your employer registers you with ÖGK. This card is your proof of insurance—present it at every doctor visit. Replacement cards cost €12 if lost.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Kassenarzt vs. Wahlarzt</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Kassenärzte (contracted doctors) accept your e-card directly—no payment required. Wahlärzte (private doctors) charge upfront; you submit receipts to ÖGK for ~80% reimbursement. Many expats prefer Wahlärzte for shorter waits and English.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Specialists and Referrals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You can see specialists directly without GP referral in Austria. However, many specialists have limited Kassenarzt appointments—you may wait weeks. Private specialists (Wahlärzte) often have faster availability.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Emergency rooms (Notaufnahme) are free with e-card. For planned hospitalizations, ÖGK covers general ward. Private insurance adds single/double rooms. Vienna's AKH is one of Europe's largest teaching hospitals.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Finding English-Speaking Doctors</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      In Vienna and major cities, many doctors speak English. Use docfinder.at to search for doctors and filter by language. The international district (1st district, near UN) has many English-speaking practices catering to expats and diplomats.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Prescription system:</strong> Austrian pharmacies (Apotheken) require prescriptions for most medications. Get prescriptions from your doctor on the standard form. Some medications that are over-the-counter elsewhere require prescription in Austria. Night and weekend pharmacies operate on rotation—check apothekensuche.at.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to arrange health insurance separately for my visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. For employed Red-White-Red Card holders, health insurance is automatic through ÖGK when your employer registers you. You don't need to provide separate insurance documentation for the visa. Coverage begins when employment starts.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I get 70 points if I only have a bachelor's degree?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Bachelor's gives 20 points. Add 6+ years experience (20), young age under 30 (20), German B1 (15), English B1 (10) = 85 possible without master's. Focus on what you can control: get German certification (online courses like Goethe-Institut), document all work experience carefully.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers with the Red-White-Red Card?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The initial card is tied to your employer for 2 years. To change jobs, you need a new card application with the new employer. After 2 years, you receive the "Red-White-Red Card Plus" which allows work for any employer without restrictions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is ÖGK coverage really sufficient or do I need private insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          ÖGK covers all essential healthcare—GP, specialists, hospitals, prescriptions. Most expats find it sufficient. Private supplement adds convenience (private rooms, any doctor, shorter waits) but isn't necessary. Consider adding it after you've experienced the system.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my spouse and children join me in Austria?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouse and dependent children can apply for family reunion from the start. They receive residence permits allowing family life. Spouse can work with a work permit. Children can attend school. Family members are covered by ÖGK if spouse works; otherwise, they need insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Standard path is 5 years of legal residence. With German A2 certification and integration courses, you can apply after 4 years. You must have been legally employed, no long breaks in residence, and meet income requirements. The Red-White-Red Card counts toward this time.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Austria's Red-White-Red Card offers a clear path for skilled workers willing to meet the 70-point threshold. The points system rewards qualifications and experience, making it accessible even with moderate salaries. Vienna's tech scene is growing, quality of life is exceptional, and the healthcare system through ÖGK is excellent.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      For insurance, the Austrian system is simpler than Germany's. There's no choice between public and private—everyone employed gets ÖGK automatically. Coverage is comprehensive, costs are predictable (deducted from salary), and there's no visa documentation hassle. Supplementary private insurance is optional for those wanting extra convenience.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The main challenge is the points threshold. If you're a bachelor's holder with limited experience, you may need to invest in German language certification or gain more experience before qualifying. But for master's/PhD holders or those with 6+ years experience, the path is straightforward. Vienna is increasingly attractive for tech workers who want German-speaking Europe without Berlin's chaos or Switzerland's cost.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        The Red-White-Red Card requires 70 points but provides automatic ÖGK health insurance through employment—no separate application needed. Vienna offers excellent quality of life, growing tech sector, and simpler insurance than Germany. Calculate your points first, get German certification if borderline, and plan for the 8-12 week processing time.
      </p>
